    5/5
    (Translated by Google) Eating a traditional chicken Cous Cous, in the Medina of Tangier.
    There are still doubts about the original meaning of the word couscous, taken …
    (Translated by Google) Eating a traditional chicken Cous Cous, in the Medina of Tangier.
    There are still doubts about the original meaning of the word couscous, taken from the Berber word "al kuskus". According to some, it designates the amount of food that a bird catches with its beak and kneads it into tiny balls to feed its young, others consider it a Frenchization of the expression “rac keskés” (to grind finely) and explain that it is a phonetic deviation of the terms koskos, keuscas, koskosú and kuskús, used in different regions of Africa to designate a clay or esparto container with holes, which fits into the mouth of the pot and contains water and broth; container in which the semolina is put to be steamed. That name has since been given to the preparation made in that vessel.
    (Original)
    Comiendo un tradicional Cous Cous de pollo, en la Medina de Tanger.
    Todavía existen dudas sobre el significado original de la palabra cuscús, tomada del vocablo beréber “al kuskus“. Según algunos, designa la cantidad de alimento que un ave coge con su pico y que amasa en minúsculas bolitas para alimentar a sus crías, otros la consideran un afrancesamiento de la expresión “rac keskés“ (triturar finamente) y explican que se trata de una desviación fonética de los términos koskos, keuscas, koskosú y kuskús, empleados en diferentes regiones de África para designar un recipiente de arcilla o de esparto provisto de agujeros, que se adapta a la boca de la marmita y que contiene agua y caldo; recipiente en el cual se mete la sémola para ser cocida al vapor. Ese nombre ha sido dado después a la preparación hecha en esa vasija.

    Ancien Medina

    The walled Ancien Medina is entered through centuries-old gates, including Bab Al Bahr, which offers access to the ramparts for port views. The Tangier American Legation Museum traces local history, and there are displays of pottery and Roman relics in the Kasbah Museum, built around a courtyard. Alleys off Rue Siaghine are lined with shops selling rugs and spices, and lead to the landmark Grand Socco square.
